[Ben and audience laugh}

00:03:53.419 --> 00:04:00.430
Fitz: Hello, my name is Fitz. Hi, Fitz.

00:04:00.430 --> 00:04:01.430
[audience laughs]

00:04:01.430 --> 00:04:13.480
How many people in here are, are tech leads,
or technical leadership roles? All right.

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:21.970
How many people here thought this was a different
talk? Alright, ha!

00:04:21.970 --> 00:04:23.009
[audience laughs]

00:04:23.009 --> 00:04:34.310
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, so we're, we're gonna take a couple
different angles with this, but first thing

00:04:34.310 --> 00:04:45.710
we wanna do is sort of, if we wanna a-, attack
this, if we wanna define what the problem

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:56.599
is. And, a-, as we see it, that oftentimes
leadership isn't intentional. Some people

00:04:56.599 --> 00:05:04.340
don't really wanna get into it, but no matter
what happens, there's always gonna be someone,

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:05.860
sort of, leading the way.

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:12.159
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right. I mean, if you take a bunch
of engineers and you put them on a project,

00:05:12.159 --> 00:05:20.270
even if no one is assigned to be the leader
what you will find is after awhile there's

00:05:20.270 --> 00:05:28.010
some self-organization that happens, right?
And somebody starts becoming the person with

00:05:28.010 --> 00:05:36.840
the big picture; the person who becomes sort
of the main point of contact, right?

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:43.090
It starts maybe inadvertently organizing people,
dividing up tasks, right? I mean, even if

00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:48.500
they don't have official authority, it, it,
they sort of fall in to that role and people

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:55.800
give them that authority, right? Because it
has to be done; it doesn't scale otherwise.

00:05:55.800 --> 00:06:02.379
&gt;&gt;Fitz: But, they start resolving conflicts
and, and driving things toward consensus.

00:06:02.379 --> 00:06:11.210
But, the-, they step into the role of the
big picture person because every project really

00:06:11.210 --> 00:06:13.740
needs someone to do that.

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:17.850
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right. And I guess, I, I've, I've been
thinking about this because I see it happens

00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:22.960
to a lot of people. I know it happened to
me when we were working on the Subversion

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:31.599
project for five years. It started out with
just a few of us in a closet writing code

00:06:31.599 --> 00:06:41.150
and by the end of it, it, I was an I-R-C all
day long eff-, effectively managing Internet

00:06:41.150 --> 00:06:46.960
volunteers who were working on the code.

00:06:46.960 --> 00:07:00.039
I wasn't much code in myself anywhere; I was
just organizing people and noted that, they're

00:07:00.039 --> 00:07:07.250
not my reports, right? But, I was leading
them anyway. And I, I call this the "accidental

00:07:07.250 --> 00:07:11.039
manager"; I guess maybe that's the best way
to put it. And is, has anyone had that experience

00:07:11.039 --> 00:07:14.530
here? Like, become accidental managers? Yeah,
right, I mean you're like, "How, how did I

00:07:14.530 --> 00:07:18.039
get here? What happened?" And we're here to
say it's not a big deal. It's not; it's not

00:07:18.039 --> 00:07:21.289
the end of the world. It's actually ok.

00:07:21.289 --> 00:07:22.460
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:23.629
&gt;&gt;Ben: So--

00:07:23.629 --> 00:07:32.960
&gt;&gt;Fitz: And so, but first we wanna talk semantics,
ok? And I'm not talking about the Semantic

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:38.301
Web here, but, I have an issue with the word
"manager", ok? And--

00:07:38.301 --> 00:07:39.301
[Ben laughs]

00:07:39.301 --> 00:07:47.560
do the Will Smith thing that's manager is
wh-, is old and busted and "leader" is the

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:48.740
new hotness, ok?

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:49.740
[laughter]

00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:54.639
So, old and busted; new hotness, right? Manager
really is a four-letter word, ok?

00:07:54.639 --> 00:08:00.139
&gt;&gt;Ben: Why is it a loaded term?

00:08:00.139 --> 00:08:06.509
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, it, it, it evolved out of the
Industrial Revolution, right? You didn't have

00:08:06.509 --> 00:08:08.970
managers three-four hundred years ago, or
project managers, or people looking to maximize

00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:09.970
their resources.

00:08:09.970 --> 00:08:10.970
[Ben laughs]

00:08:10.970 --> 00:08:12.711
Management is, is, it came out about the Industrial
Revolution, the assembly line, right? If,

00:08:12.711 --> 00:08:19.173
if you're gonna have somebody in a line stuffing
meat into a can, you need somebody--

00:08:19.173 --> 00:08:20.173
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yum.

00:08:20.173 --> 00:08:23.690
&gt;&gt;Fitz: to manage people stuffing meat into
a can.

00:08:23.690 --> 00:08:24.830
[audience laughs]

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:33.240
But this works. It's very effective, this
sort of carrot and stick routine when you

00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:36.310
have people doing something by rote, right?

00:08:36.310 --> 00:08:43.719
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right. You want to maximize efficiency
by waving carrots and sticks at them.

00:08:43.719 --> 00:08:47.100
&gt;&gt;Fitz: And you want people to be compliant
and listen, ok?

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:48.100
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yup, yup.

00:08:48.100 --> 00:08:57.430
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, this is, and al-, this is some
of the stuff we're talking about here comes

00:08:57.430 --> 00:09:05.580
a lot from Dan Pink. If you haven't seen his
Tech talk we highly recommend it. We'll talk

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:09.470
a little bit more about that towards the end.

00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:10.910
&gt;&gt;Ben: Great stuff.

00:09:10.910 --> 00:09:17.149
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, so this traditional management
mechanism works really well when you're managing

00:09:17.149 --> 00:09:18.360
people like this. Ok?

00:09:18.360 --> 00:09:19.360
[laughter]

00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:29.980
It's really great if you have nothing that
requires any sort of thought, but it's a colossal

00:09:29.980 --> 00:09:33.560
failure if you're managing something that
is, is complex, or requires any sort of creativity.

00:09:33.560 --> 00:09:35.300
&gt;&gt;Ben: Like software engineering.

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:37.470
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Like software engineering, exactly.

00:09:37.470 --> 00:09:38.470
[Ben laughs]

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:41.810
And so, as a result, this creates conflict.

00:09:41.810 --> 00:09:50.050
&gt;&gt;Ben: It's also a reason why, why managers
are hated, right? I mean, there's this, i-,

00:09:50.050 --> 00:10:01.820
in engineering, just the word manager. "Oh,
do you have a manager?" It's like, it's almost

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:15.130
like the word itself implies conflict or attention,
right? And so, I mean, there's a lot of reason

00:10:15.130 --> 00:10:28.389
for that. We have, there's a reason Dilbert
has this stereotype pointy hair. Actually--

00:10:28.389 --> 00:10:33.480
&gt;&gt;Fitz: You could do that pretty easily.

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:40.970
&gt;&gt;Ben: I can almost; I can almost make my
hair pointy if I pull it out, right? I mean,

00:10:40.970 --> 00:10:45.600
th-, lets talk about that Dilbert manager
stereotype, right? They have no technical

00:10:45.600 --> 00:10:55.290
ability, they're insecure, they get no respect
f-, because of that, from their reports. They

00:10:55.290 --> 00:11:02.649
don't respect the reports back. They ignore
any past accomplishments of their reports.

00:11:02.649 --> 00:11:10.470
They're, they're hired like zookeepers, to
sort of caged people, like you don't trust

00:11:10.470 --> 00:11:11.880
them. And, yeah--

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:16.950
&gt;&gt;Fitz: But, and a lot of them are concerned
with their own self promotion and, and survival

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:30.449
as opposed to removing obstacles for their
team, which is really what a manager should

00:11:30.449 --> 00:11:38.490
be doing. But, but for all these reasons this
is why that most engineers don't wanna be

00:11:38.490 --> 00:11:55.870
managers. I, I mean, I, I sort of became a
manager. I mean, my thought of managers was

00:11:55.870 --> 00:12:00.910
always management according to the Peter Principle,
right?

00:12:00.910 --> 00:12:02.320
[Ben laughs]

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:12.120
That's the principle that you always get promoted
one level beyond your capabilities, ok?

00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:23.959
&gt;&gt;Ben: Well, give me, give me an example of
that because I discovered a lot of people

00:12:23.959 --> 00:12:31.050
have never heard of Peter Principle. We're
just old.

00:12:31.050 --> 00:12:36.300
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Like, an example of that?

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:45.810
&gt;&gt;Ben: Well, I answer, I mean, I mean the
classic example is you have a software engineer

00:12:45.810 --> 00:12:53.639
who is an amazing programmer and they keep
getting promoted because they're an amazing

00:12:53.639 --> 00:13:04.449
programmer. But, then the way most businesses
are set up, management is "higher" than software

00:13:04.449 --> 00:13:19.790
engineering so you get to the top of the programming
chain, and if you want to get promoted then

00:13:19.790 --> 00:13:27.290
you have to become a manager, right? And suddenly,
now you have the world's worst manager and

00:13:27.290 --> 00:13:29.220
you've lost the world's best coder.

00:13:29.220 --> 00:13:30.220
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:13:30.220 --> 00:13:32.590
&gt;&gt;Ben: And that's, that's the classic scenario--

00:13:32.590 --> 00:13:34.079
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Double failure.

00:13:34.079 --> 00:13:43.620
&gt;&gt;Ben: that you see happen over and over,
right?

00:13:43.620 --> 00:13:49.899
&gt;&gt;Fitz: But th-, but the general thing is
most engineers don't consider management to

00:13:49.899 --> 00:13:56.100
be real work. You feel less productive. When
I first met-

00:13:56.100 --> 00:13:57.100
[Ben laughs]

00:13:57.100 --> 00:14:02.639
moved from engineer to tech lead and then
eventually managing people, I felt like I

00:14:02.639 --> 00:14:12.190
did nothing. I came home the other day and
said "What did I do all day?" I'm like, "I

00:14:12.190 --> 00:14:18.060
talked to people and I sent email." I'm a
human router, right?

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:19.060
[Ben laughs]

00:14:19.060 --> 00:14:20.959
It was just like, it's awful, I mean--

00:14:20.959 --> 00:14:25.829
&gt;&gt;Ben: It's hard to measure. It's really hard
to measure.

00:14:25.829 --> 00:14:29.899
&gt;&gt;Fitz: --It, it, it's almost impossible to
measure other than your general sense of malaise,

00:14:29.899 --> 00:14:30.899
right?

00:14:30.899 --> 00:14:34.760
&gt;&gt;Ben: Or perhaps, what I discovered is maybe
it's something to can measure on a long-term

00:14:34.760 --> 00:14:44.360
timescale, right? If you're an engineer, you
can sit down at the end of the week. "Oh,

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:50.120
I wrote this much code and these features
have solved 15 bugs", right? When you're a

00:14:50.120 --> 00:14:54.990
manager, it's like, "Well, over the quarter,
our team achieved this." And I think it's

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:56.350
partially my fault.

00:14:56.350 --> 00:14:57.350
[laughter]

00:14:57.350 --> 00:14:58.350
Right? So, so it's harder.

00:14:58.350 --> 00:14:59.350
&gt;&gt;Fitz: But, well, let's talk about what,
what an engineering leader is.

00:14:59.350 --> 00:15:00.350
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right.

00:15:00.350 --> 00:15:14.440
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Ok? When y-, and I wanna really switch
more to the general leader thing. But, a,

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:23.810
a leader is not a General in this case. You're
not talking about Patton. It's not somebody

00:15:23.810 --> 00:15:32.060
who barks orders at people, it's not someone
whose team is there to serve them; a real

00:15:32.060 --> 00:15:35.990
leader is someone who is there to serve, right?

00:15:35.990 --> 00:15:36.990
[Ben laughs]

00:15:36.990 --> 00:15:44.579
It's someone who serves the team, ok? Y-,
you're role as a leader is really, more than

00:15:44.579 --> 00:15:53.440
anything else, to remove obstacles for your
team. So, to grease the wheels, to give advice

00:15:53.440 --> 00:16:07.959
and guidance when it's l-, asked for, to help
people with their careers as well. It, but

00:16:07.959 --> 00:16:11.560
it's, it's not about this just barking orders--

00:16:11.560 --> 00:16:12.769
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right.

00:16:12.769 --> 00:16:18.190
&gt;&gt;Fitz: there's gotta be an element of trust
there.

00:16:18.190 --> 00:16:25.370
&gt;&gt;Ben: Absolutely. And, and the other thing
you need to think about, as a manager, is,

00:16:25.370 --> 00:16:32.140
is y-, you're responsible for two things;
both the technical and the social part of

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:41.850
the team, right? And what, a, a lot of places
where I'll see an engineer promoted to management

00:16:41.850 --> 00:16:49.990
accidentally, they're only still focused on
the technical side and they ignore the social

00:16:49.990 --> 00:16:55.709
issues. And they're actually important.

00:16:55.709 --> 00:17:06.140
If you ignore the social problems, you will
have morale problems, the team will fall apart,

00:17:06.140 --> 00:17:19.860
you'll, you'll, people will be fight-, I mean,
you don't think it's possible but then you

00:17:19.860 --> 00:17:35.020
start managing people and you notice it happens.
And a lot of people put blinders on, right?

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:42.470
Likewise, you don't want a manager who's purely
social, either, right? A manager should have

00:17:42.470 --> 00:17:48.179
some technical skill, should be able to engage
the team, right? And--

00:17:48.179 --> 00:17:51.179
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Understand what they're doing and--

00:17:51.179 --> 00:17:52.179
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yep.

00:17:52.179 --> 00:17:58.710
&gt;&gt;Fitz: and be smart enough to get, get their
nose out of it, right?

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:08.360
&gt;&gt;Ben: So, you need a mix of both. You need,
you need to really think about both things

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:09.360
all the time.

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:16.159
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right. So, so to touch on the, on
the group therapy aspect of this--

00:18:16.159 --> 00:18:17.309
[Ben laughs]

00:18:17.309 --> 00:18:27.630
leadership is not a waste of time. It's a
very important role and it's a way of getting

00:18:27.630 --> 00:18:35.020
more done than you can do by yourself. So,
it's a way of scaling yourself, right?

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:47.650
&gt;&gt;Ben: I remember one of my, one of my first
managers I asked, I said, he had just into

00:18:47.650 --> 00:18:53.841
management, right? And I said, "You're not
writing code anymore, how you feel about that?"

00:18:53.841 --> 00:19:00.350
And he's like, "Well, I realize now by, by
managing you guys, like, way, way more code

00:19:00.350 --> 00:19:08.659
is being written than if I were just jumping
in and, and coding with you."

00:19:08.659 --> 00:19:09.740
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Yeah.

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:17.670
&gt;&gt;Ben: Like, that's the impact I have. So,
you can actually, it's hard to quantify, but

00:19:17.670 --> 00:19:18.870
it's real, right?

00:19:18.870 --> 00:19:28.950
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right. So, so that sets the stage
when we talk about. And the best way, I think,

00:19:28.950 --> 00:19:37.200
to sort of explain what we're talking about
here is what makes a good leader. Again, according

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:44.140
to our opinions and we have very little experience
here, so you shouldn't listen to us,

00:19:44.140 --> 00:19:45.500
[Ben laughs]

00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:50.720
is to talk about the negative side, right,
the antipatterns.

00:19:50.720 --> 00:19:54.020
&gt;&gt;Ben: We'll start with antipatterns.

00:19:54.020 --> 00:19:58.910
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Ok, we'll start with antipatterns.
Number one--

00:19:58.910 --> 00:20:08.460
&gt;&gt;Ben: Hurray! Be everyone's friend. And this
is tricky, right, especially if you manage

00:20:08.460 --> 00:20:09.830
a friend--

00:20:09.830 --> 00:20:17.970
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Especially if y-, you're in a team
and you're suddenly managing the team or leading

00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:18.970
the team.

00:20:18.970 --> 00:20:29.230
&gt;&gt;Ben: --To suddenly switch from peer to manager.
Sometimes it's a problem, sometimes it's not

00:20:29.230 --> 00:20:38.669
but, it's actually possible to lead the team
with a soft touch. Like, I always say the

00:20:38.669 --> 00:20:46.770
best kind of leadership is leadership you
can't really see if it's happening, but it's

00:20:46.770 --> 00:20:50.970
not obvious, right? And that, that's fine.

00:20:50.970 --> 00:20:54.311
I think that works and it's not about becoming
everybody's best friend, but it's not about

00:20:54.311 --> 00:20:59.440
being distant, either. One of the best pieces
of advice I've heard is like, eat lunch with

00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:07.760
you team, right? Don't, don't sit in your
corner office with your door closed.

00:21:07.760 --> 00:21:21.789
You need to be hearing what they, what are
they talking about, what are they struggling

00:21:21.789 --> 00:21:35.620
with every day? Like, and that, that's like
the same as being their friend, but--

00:21:35.620 --> 00:21:36.860
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:21:36.860 --> 00:21:40.510
&gt;&gt;Ben: but it is being involved, right?

00:21:40.510 --> 00:21:44.970
&gt;Fitz: You can, the point is you can communicate
and--

00:21:44.970 --> 00:21:45.970
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right.

00:21:45.970 --> 00:21:51.940
&gt;&gt;Fitz: be social with your team without necessarily
being their friend. If you're, if you're someone,

00:21:51.940 --> 00:21:54.909
everyone's friend, it really destroys the
ability to sort of, sometimes you have to

00:21:54.909 --> 00:22:02.919
sort of have to be stick and not the carrot,
in some cases, and even--

00:22:02.919 --> 00:22:05.730
&gt;&gt;Ben: To deliver bad news or--

00:22:05.730 --> 00:22:13.230
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Or deliver bad news or, or just push
someone in, in, in a general direction.

00:22:13.230 --> 00:22:14.230
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right.

00:22:14.230 --> 00:22:17.960
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, so, the next thing is the parent-child
relationship, right? Ok?

00:22:17.960 --> 00:22:18.960
[Ben laughs]

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:22.529
People will, will behave the way that you
treat them, ok? Now, so if you put a bunch

00:22:22.529 --> 00:22:29.640
of bars up, up, on the windows and lock all
the doors, everyone's gonna behave like a

00:22:29.640 --> 00:22:37.409
bunch of caged animals. If you treat people
like children then they're gonna behave like

00:22:37.409 --> 00:22:41.000
children, ok? W-, there's a conference--

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:42.200
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yes.

00:22:42.200 --> 00:22:52.490
&gt;&gt;Fitz: that we put on in Chicago and I, I
got the conference facility all set up and

00:22:52.490 --> 00:23:07.240
I went over and talked to guy and he showed
me around and he said, "Here's the keys. I'll

00:23:07.240 --> 00:23:11.539
see ya, I'll see ya in three days."

00:23:11.539 --> 00:23:14.570
&gt;&gt;Ben: To the whole building.

00:23:14.570 --> 00:23:23.289
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Yeah, and he's like, "This is where
this is." And that sort of thing. And it was

00:23:23.289 --> 00:23:34.150
an incredible amount of responsibility put
upon me and there, and I was very appreciative

00:23:34.150 --> 00:23:45.480
of that but I knew that I was, I was the one
who had to take care of the place to make

00:23:45.480 --> 00:23:50.550
sure nothing really bad happened and that
sort of thing.

00:23:50.550 --> 00:23:58.299
&gt;&gt;Ben: What about, one of the things I like
about working at Google, the way our IT department

00:23:58.299 --> 00:24:03.740
works, its set up as a service to help us
rather than to cage us. Like, most IT departments

00:24:03.740 --> 00:24:10.299
treat you like naughty children and how can
we stop you from doing the bad things, right?

00:24:10.299 --> 00:24:15.861
And we're gonna restrict you in every corner.
And Google's IT department is, well, no, we

00:24:15.861 --> 00:24:20.720
think you're a grown up and if you need something
come and ask, and we'll give it to you, right?

00:24:20.720 --> 00:24:24.731
Otherwise, we trust you to behave and I think
that's a--

00:24:24.731 --> 00:24:34.130
&gt;&gt;Fitz: And, and, there's some controversial
s-, apar-, a, some controversial pe-, ideas

00:24:34.130 --> 00:24:43.370
in here, too. Like, you may have heard that
Netflix has no vacation. Their, their vacation

00:24:43.370 --> 00:24:52.870
policy is you no fixed number of vacation
days. You take it when you need it, right?

00:24:52.870 --> 00:24:59.910
And that's, that's, I think it's really interesting
and I think it's really, I'd love to see how

00:24:59.910 --> 00:25:00.910
that works--

00:25:00.910 --> 00:25:03.540
&gt;&gt;Ben: Peer pressure?

00:25:03.540 --> 00:25:11.790
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, it's, it's a little bit of everything
but you're not treating people like children

00:25:11.790 --> 00:25:16.740
there, it's, it's an extreme, but it's something
interesting to contemplate.

00:25:16.740 --> 00:25:22.320
&gt;&gt;Ben: More antipatterns. Micromanaging, I
don't think there's a lot to say here, right?

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:25.360
This is the ultimate sign--

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:36.590
&gt;&gt;Fitz: What I want you to say here is it's
about distrust.

00:25:36.590 --> 00:25:39.039
[Ben laughs]

00:25:39.039 --> 00:25:43.929
&gt;&gt;Ben: That word, right?

00:25:43.929 --> 00:25:48.970
&gt;&gt;Fitz: That word right there.

00:25:48.970 --> 00:25:58.610
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right. So, it's about distrust, right?
This is, this is the classic Dilbert situation.

00:25:58.610 --> 00:26:06.279
And honestly, if, if, if you start micromanaging
people, again, they get used to it, right?

00:26:06.279 --> 00:26:17.240
They start behaving like children, like they
stop doing work unless you poke them every

00:26:17.240 --> 00:26:24.081
day. Are you done, yet? Are you done, yet?
Are you done, yet? It's not what you want.

00:26:24.081 --> 00:26:29.799
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, it can be tempting if you're
very, if you're a very technical person that's

00:26:29.799 --> 00:26:34.600
moved into this role, it can be very tempting
sometimes because you possibly understand

00:26:34.600 --> 00:26:40.631
more than someone who's just starting, or
someone's who's a little more junior. And

00:26:40.631 --> 00:26:44.809
the temptation, in some cases, is to give
them A-B-C-D type directions.

00:26:44.809 --> 00:26:48.539
&gt;&gt;Ben: Instead of letting them figure it out.

00:26:48.539 --> 00:26:49.539
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Exactly, exactly. But that leads us
into the next thing. Sometimes, micromanagement

00:26:49.539 --> 00:26:54.620
is necessary if you follow the next pa-, antipattern,
which is hiring a bunch of pushovers.

00:26:54.620 --> 00:26:55.690
[Ben laughs]

00:26:55.690 --> 00:27:05.310
You wind up, basically, with a team that can't
move on its own and they, they require on

00:27:05.310 --> 00:27:13.480
you to make every move. And, you need a team
that's gonna power itself, that's not gonna

00:27:13.480 --> 00:27:19.929
wait for commands. And so my general rule
of thumb has always been

00:27:19.929 --> 00:27:20.929
[Ben laughs]

00:27:20.929 --> 00:27:27.340
since I, I, I first started managing about
12-13 years ago but then quit because I had

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:32.590
this horrible experience, which is why I'm
here today. But, it was, I hire people smarter

00:27:32.590 --> 00:27:38.570
than me, which isn't too hard for me, but
you get people who are gonna just get things

00:27:38.570 --> 00:27:42.419
done, who are gonna make things happen, where
you don't have to worry about them not understanding

00:27:42.419 --> 00:27:47.590
what's going on. It, I, at the time, I, I
worked with another guy who, who made a, he

00:27:47.590 --> 00:27:54.100
actually embodied this anitpattern. I hired
all these people that were smarter than me

00:27:54.100 --> 00:28:03.130
and they went off and did amazing things and
he hired a bunch of people that he could push

00:28:03.130 --> 00:28:11.529
and poke around. And he loved it because he
had this team of flunkies that he could just

00:28:11.529 --> 00:28:13.919
push and poke around.

00:28:13.919 --> 00:28:16.890
&gt;&gt;Ben: Like a power trip, right?

00:28:16.890 --> 00:28:24.430
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Yeah, and as his team got bigger,
he started working longer and longer and longer

00:28:24.430 --> 00:28:28.399
hours. And he would just sort of--

00:28:28.399 --> 00:28:30.660
&gt;&gt;Ben: It doesn't scale.

00:28:30.660 --> 00:28:33.490
&gt;&gt;Fitz: It doesn't scale, right?

00:28:33.490 --> 00:28:34.629
[Ben laughs]

00:28:34.629 --> 00:28:41.120
And he was sort of miserable and eventually
wound up leaving. But--

00:28:41.120 --> 00:28:56.610
&gt;&gt;Ben: Well, I, I, sort of I think related
to this is the next pattern which is to compromise

00:28:56.610 --> 00:29:08.640
when you hire. A lot of, a lot of companies
will see, "We're, oh gosh; we're short-handed

00:29:08.640 --> 00:29:17.470
on this team. We need two people, so let's
interview 20 and we'll just hire the best

00:29:17.470 --> 00:29:20.150
two no matter what."

00:29:20.150 --> 00:29:22.170
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Bad idea.

00:29:22.170 --> 00:29:23.510
[Ben laughs]

00:29:23.510 --> 00:29:26.190
&gt;&gt;Ben: Very bad idea.

00:29:26.190 --> 00:29:40.559
&gt;&gt;Fitz: B-, because performance and your quality
is gonna go way down and if you have really

00:29:40.559 --> 00:29:49.980
good people on the team, they're gonna go
way away from you.

00:29:49.980 --> 00:29:51.550
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yep.

00:29:51.550 --> 00:30:00.980
&gt;&gt;Fitz: And they're just basically gonna leave.
So, that ties a lot in again to the next antipattern,

00:30:00.980 --> 00:30:04.150
which is to ignore low performers.

00:30:04.150 --> 00:30:12.091
&gt;&gt;Ben: Holy cow. Has anyone ever worked with
a low performer that nobody did anything about?

00:30:12.091 --> 00:30:22.660
Right? There's nothing more, yeah, wow, there's
a lot of you. There's nothing more aggravating.

00:30:22.660 --> 00:30:33.890
Its like, "Oh my gosh, this person is dragging
down our whole team, and I can't say anything,

00:30:33.890 --> 00:30:44.380
and why isn't the manager saying anything
to this person, or doing anything about it?"

00:30:44.380 --> 00:30:52.020
I mean, like you said, it will cause the best
people on the team to leave and find another

00:30:52.020 --> 00:30:54.580
team or another job.

00:30:54.580 --> 00:31:07.279
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, and this is probably the hardest
thing to do as, as a leader of, of a team,

00:31:07.279 --> 00:31:19.080
is to work with low performers. I, I think,
there's a couple reasons for it. The main

00:31:19.080 --> 00:31:29.159
reason that I've seen is you wait too long.
You sort of like, if I don't look over there,

00:31:29.159 --> 00:31:30.940
they'll get better, right?

00:31:30.940 --> 00:31:32.269
&gt;&gt;Ben: Hope-, hopefully.

00:31:32.269 --> 00:31:35.370
&gt;&gt;Fitz: It's gonna get better, yeah, hopefully.

00:31:35.370 --> 00:31:36.370
[Ben laughs]

00:31:36.370 --> 00:31:43.360
Hope, yeah, code powered by hope. I-, i-,
it's just gonna get better and what happens

00:31:43.360 --> 00:31:50.429
when you do that is you wait until it's too
late. And you eventually reach a point where

00:31:50.429 --> 00:32:01.919
it's hopeless and the only thing you can see
is, "How do I get rid of this person?" Ok?

00:32:01.919 --> 00:32:04.440
So, if you sort of--

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:13.450
&gt;&gt;Ben: And then that's the first conversation
you have--

00:32:13.450 --> 00:32:14.450
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:32:14.450 --> 00:32:18.590
&gt;&gt;Ben: with that person, when you've already
decided that it's doomed. How do you even

00:32:18.590 --> 00:32:27.870
rehabilitate or give them a chance to get
better? So, you've already made this decision.

00:32:27.870 --> 00:32:38.380
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, you, you made this mental sort
of step in your head where you can't, can't

00:32:38.380 --> 00:32:50.909
think about that. So, if you step in early
you can actually help to manage them up or

00:32:50.909 --> 00:33:01.399
out, as opposed to just like, "How do I get
rid of this person?" Ok? It's not just gonna

00:33:01.399 --> 00:33:07.000
get better. There's just, there's just doesn't
happen.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:19.990
&gt;&gt;Ben: I think, I think the next point sort
of is a generalization is which we talked

00:33:19.990 --> 00:33:28.309
about earlier is just there are human problems
on your team. Not every problem is software

00:33:28.309 --> 00:33:34.559
development, is about writing code, or technical
problems, right? People, sometimes people

00:33:34.559 --> 00:33:36.850
don't get along. Sometimes--

00:33:36.850 --> 00:33:42.019
&gt;&gt;Fitz: People problems are much harder than
code problems.

00:33:42.019 --> 00:33:43.019
[Ben laughs]

00:33:43.019 --> 00:33:44.019
&gt;&gt;Ben: Much harder.

00:33:44.019 --> 00:33:51.590
&gt;&gt;Fitz: I have yet to find a bug that's as
hard as a people problem.

00:33:51.590 --> 00:34:00.950
&gt;&gt;Ben: Well, cause, it's, it's fuzzy. People
are fuzzy and grey and computers are not that

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:01.950
way.

00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:05.200
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Compilers are so much more consistent.

00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:15.670
&gt;&gt;Ben: Exactly. Sometimes, well, I would,
I guess well, this is a, this is a, sort of

00:34:15.670 --> 00:34:26.520
a scary story. But, one of the things I see
missing sometimes and th-, if you have like

00:34:26.520 --> 00:34:34.000
a manager who's all technical, not interested
in social aspects at all, the thing that,

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:37.020
that always lacking is just simple empathy,
right?

00:34:37.020 --> 00:34:48.290
That's sometimes all you need just to keep
the social wheels greased. I had a friend

00:34:48.290 --> 00:34:57.190
who was working at a company, he had his first
kid, got a couple weeks off on paternity leave,

00:34:57.190 --> 00:35:04.130
came back was still very sleep-deprived, discombobulated
and he basically, was only working with one

00:35:04.130 --> 00:35:08.110
other person in his office.

00:35:08.110 --> 00:35:18.870
There was just the two of them. And he said,
"You know I'm gonna be working from home and

00:35:18.870 --> 00:35:25.060
doing I-R-C and chatting." And his manager
found out and said, "No, you cannot work part

00:35:25.060 --> 00:35:35.440
time from home at all. No, no, you have to
be in the office." And why not? And basically

00:35:35.440 --> 00:35:42.950
said, "Look, you have to be in the office.
If, it's more important and--" What was the

00:35:42.950 --> 00:35:43.950
phrase he said?

00:35:43.950 --> 00:35:49.510
&gt;&gt;Fritz: He said, "People have kids all the
time."

00:35:49.510 --> 00:35:52.030
&gt;&gt;Ben: "Get over it."

00:35:52.030 --> 00:35:53.290
[audience laughs]

00:35:53.290 --> 00:35:55.820
&gt;&gt;Fritz: "Get over it."

00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:58.530
&gt;&gt;Ben: It's like, what? I mean, that's amazing
to--

00:35:58.530 --> 00:36:04.290
&gt;&gt;Fritz: So, I can see the point of wanting
someone to come into the office and work,

00:36:04.290 --> 00:36:07.970
but that's just the wrong motivational thing
to say.

00:36:07.970 --> 00:36:10.420
&gt;&gt;Ben: Not, yeah, not understanding. So,--

00:36:10.420 --> 00:36:13.330
&gt;&gt;Fritz: It's the rage button, the rage--

00:36:13.330 --> 00:36:14.380
[Ben laughs]

00:36:14.380 --> 00:36:16.890
&gt;&gt;Ben: So, happiness level--

00:36:16.890 --> 00:36:24.100
&gt;&gt;Fritz: So you have to pay attention to happiness
levels--

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:25.100
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right.

00:36:25.100 --> 00:36:33.810
&gt;&gt;Fritz: You have to pay attention to the
happiness levels of your team and it sounds

00:36:33.810 --> 00:36:40.790
all like, fluffy and crazy, but you know,
you really have to understand what, to be

00:36:40.790 --> 00:36:47.700
able to, to have a productive team and be
a, a good leader, the thing to understand

00:36:47.700 --> 00:36:52.460
are people happy with the product, are they
happy with where they're going, with how much

00:36:52.460 --> 00:36:57.760
they're working, with the company. I mean,
it's a lot of different things you have to

00:36:57.760 --> 00:36:59.260
be sensitive to.

00:36:59.260 --> 00:37:01.910
&gt;&gt;Ben: What do they call it? E-Q?

00:37:01.910 --> 00:37:07.470
&gt;&gt;Fritz: E-Q, yeah, Emotional Quality, Emotional
Quotient or something like that, yeah. Something

00:37:07.470 --> 00:37:10.470
completely unmeasureable and fuzzy that engineers
love.

00:37:10.470 --> 00:37:17.750
&gt;&gt;Ben: Let's, let's talk about good things
you can do, which I guess we've sort of been

00:37:17.750 --> 00:37:18.960
doing it implicitly.

00:37:18.960 --> 00:37:22.740
&gt;&gt;Fritz: This is the boring part. You can
check your email--

00:37:22.740 --> 00:37:23.740
[Ben laughs]

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:29.020
&gt;&gt;Ben: Honesty is one of the biggest foundations
for everything, right? If, if you're stuck,

00:37:29.020 --> 00:37:39.790
if you don't know what to do, go ahead and
say so, right? Nobody expects you to be perfect

00:37:39.790 --> 00:37:45.810
or to have all the answers, right? Well, actually,
you should talk about the compliment sandwich.

00:37:45.810 --> 00:37:47.910
This is the, the thing--

00:37:47.910 --> 00:37:49.600
&gt;&gt;Fritz: The compliment sandwich--

00:37:49.600 --> 00:37:53.260
&gt;&gt;Ben: the, the dishonest way to get heard.

00:37:53.260 --> 00:37:57.765
&gt;&gt;Fritz: How many people have heard of the
compliment sandwich? Ok.

00:37:57.765 --> 00:37:59.530
&gt;&gt;Ben: Let's watch, something

00:37:59.530 --> 00:38:08.400
&gt;&gt;Fritz: --Ok, so for the rest of you, so
the compliment sandwich is this, it this traditional

00:38:08.400 --> 00:38:16.310
management technique for delivering harsh
feedback. You come into the room and you say,

00:38:16.310 --> 00:38:26.610
"Ben, you know, you've done a really good
job, you've been a great team member and all,

00:38:26.610 --> 00:38:33.080
your code is really, really low quality, but
I like your beard." Ok?

00:38:33.080 --> 00:38:34.590
[audience laughs]

00:38:34.590 --> 00:38:39.000
And Ben walks out going, "He likes my beard
and I'm a good guy."

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:40.000
&gt;&gt;Ben: Awesome.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:46.120
&gt;&gt;Fritz: The compliment sandwich is a lie,
ok? It's like the cake, it's a lie.

00:38:46.120 --> 00:38:47.120
[Ben coughs]

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:51.420
It's just a bad idea and I, I personally think
that it's better to be constructive, straight

00:38:51.420 --> 00:38:59.670
forward, and direct while still having that
empathy for the person that you're giving

00:38:59.670 --> 00:39:08.690
it to. I like nothing better than to receive
very constructive feedback if I've done something

00:39:08.690 --> 00:39:11.070
wrong. And I mean--

00:39:11.070 --> 00:39:17.750
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right. But you have to be tactful when
you do it, right?

00:39:17.750 --> 00:39:19.150
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Yeah.

00:39:19.150 --> 00:39:24.740
&gt;&gt;Ben: Honestly does not mean compliments,
I mean--

00:39:24.740 --> 00:39:28.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Give an example of that.

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:32.350
&gt;&gt;Ben: Well, yeah. Wha-, what's a good example
of this? So--

00:39:32.350 --> 00:39:39.340
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, here's, we had a guy, we had
a guy that, that we worked with years ago

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:45.100
who was really technically strong, wanted
to argue absolutely everything, ok? Everything

00:39:45.100 --> 00:39:47.020
was an argument, ok?

00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:48.940
&gt;&gt;Ben: --Great coder though.

00:39:48.940 --> 00:39:56.410
&gt;&gt;Fitz: --Solid coder, right? Ok, so the nonconstructive
is they say, is stop being a dick and fighting

00:39:56.410 --> 00:39:59.200
with everybody, ok?

00:39:59.200 --> 00:40:07.340
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right, not the way, the way to deliver
the message.

00:40:07.340 --> 00:40:13.620
&gt;&gt;Fitz: What do you think, where do you think
that's gonna get you? They say, "Oh, wow.

00:40:13.620 --> 00:40:19.450
I was being a jerk. I should stop this."

00:40:19.450 --> 00:40:20.830
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right, right.

00:40:20.830 --> 00:40:22.660
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, so that's--

00:40:22.660 --> 00:40:28.290
&gt;&gt;Ben: What's, what's the better way, the
way you do it. I like the way you--

00:40:28.290 --> 00:40:36.980
&gt;&gt;Fitz: The, the, the better way is, and this
was explained to me by one of my previous

00:40:36.980 --> 00:40:47.950
managers, is that you're in a station and
a train's gonna come by every ten minutes

00:40:47.950 --> 00:40:59.120
all day long, ok? Now, you need to pick which
train you want to step in front of, ok?

00:40:59.120 --> 00:41:03.790
&gt;&gt;Ben: You can't stand in front of all the--

00:41:03.790 --> 00:41:15.600
&gt;&gt;Fitz: You can't step in front of every train
or you're gonna be flattened, ok? Every time

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:28.810
you step in front of one of these trains,
the engineers gotta slam on the brakes. Some

00:41:28.810 --> 00:41:32.500
of them might hit you, but they're gonna be
annoyed because you're throwing them off schedule.

00:41:32.500 --> 00:41:38.910
&gt;&gt;Ben: I think it's a way of saying "choose
your battles", right?

00:41:38.910 --> 00:41:50.800
&gt;&gt;Fitz: It's a way of saying "choose your
battles," right? But, it sounds more fun when

00:41:50.800 --> 00:41:54.070
you're talking about trains, right? Everybody
loves trains.

00:41:54.070 --> 00:41:55.070
&gt;&gt;Ben: All right, let's, let's talk about
the next pattern--

00:41:55.070 --> 00:41:59.830
&gt;&gt;Fitz: But, but the other thing about the
honesty that I wanna leave this on is there's

00:41:59.830 --> 00:42:04.010
no such thing as a temporary lapse of integrity.

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:05.530
&gt;&gt;Ben: I like that.

00:42:05.530 --> 00:42:12.330
&gt;&gt;Fitz: That's, that's something that, that
was a piece of advice that I was, and all

00:42:12.330 --> 00:42:19.910
this stuff really, a lot of this advice is
coming from advice that we've gotten from

00:42:19.910 --> 00:42:26.970
our mentors who taught us. But, that's one
of the most important things I, I, I think

00:42:26.970 --> 00:42:28.290
I've learned is the temporary lapse.

00:42:28.290 --> 00:42:29.290
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yep. Temporary lapse.

00:42:29.290 --> 00:42:33.230
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Temporary lapse of integrity ess-,
that means you have no integrity. So, that's

00:42:33.230 --> 00:42:37.770
where I think that the honesty really comes
in as important.

00:42:37.770 --> 00:42:44.400
&gt;Ben: Speaking of folks that we, that we admire,
there's, there's a manager at Google who we

00:42:44.400 --> 00:42:50.280
love and we always refer to him as a Zen Master,
right?

00:42:50.280 --> 00:42:51.280
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:42:51.280 --> 00:42:58.880
&gt;&gt;Ben: We think of him that way because he,
we're talking about, exudes calmness, right?

00:42:58.880 --> 00:42:59.880
I--

00:42:59.880 --> 00:43:06.530
&gt;&gt;Fitz: In, in, in utter chaos, I, we, we
see someone come running into his office and

00:43:06.530 --> 00:43:18.450
say, "Somebody's bombed 19 of our data centers,
oh my God!" And he's just lean back and say,

00:43:18.450 --> 00:43:23.670
"Hmm, I wonder why they didn't do 20?"

00:43:23.670 --> 00:43:24.980
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right.

00:43:24.980 --> 00:43:26.290
[audience laughs]

00:43:26.290 --> 00:43:27.290
&gt;&gt;Fitz: That's, you know--

00:43:27.290 --> 00:43:34.690
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yeah, right. So he, you want to ha-,
have, this is something that we strive for

00:43:34.690 --> 00:43:41.250
as well when we're having one-on-one's with
people, or, or in any kind of meeting, right?

00:43:41.250 --> 00:43:52.570
Is stay calm, stay focused, ask the team what
they can do to measure the problem, how they

00:43:52.570 --> 00:44:00.530
can be more productive, how, that, what, what
kinds of solutions there are. When somebody

00:44:00.530 --> 00:44:11.510
asks you for direct advice, if you have a
direct opinion, you should give it, but if

00:44:11.510 --> 00:44:19.650
you don't have an opinion you can do the psychologist
thing, right, and respond with more questions.

00:44:19.650 --> 00:44:20.650
Maybe--

00:44:20.650 --> 00:44:21.650
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well--

00:44:21.650 --> 00:44:22.650
&gt;&gt;Ben: help them Socratically.

00:44:22.650 --> 00:44:25.380
&gt;Fitz: I think you should respond with questions
off the bat first--

00:44:25.380 --> 00:44:27.580
&gt;&gt;Ben: Off the bat?

00:44:27.580 --> 00:44:36.400
&gt;&gt;Fitz: instead of, cause it's, i-, it's really
tempting to solve it. I mean, we're sol-,

00:44:36.400 --> 00:44:41.450
problem solvers by nature. Anyone who is an
engineer, you're paid to pr-, solve problems,

00:44:41.450 --> 00:44:50.210
ok? My wife loves this when I come home and
she's like, "Oh, I had a terrible day." And

00:44:50.210 --> 00:45:00.850
I'm like, "Let me fix it for you! Let me fix
it for you!" And she's like, "Just listen.

00:45:00.850 --> 00:45:06.010
Please. Don't fix it; I want you to hear me."

00:45:06.010 --> 00:45:08.680
[audience laughs and claps]

00:45:08.680 --> 00:45:15.680
&gt;&gt;Ben: That's, that's the Mars-Venus thing,
right?

00:45:15.680 --> 00:45:25.530
&gt;&gt;Fitz: That's the Mars-Venus thing, yeah.
But if you, a, a lot of the time they don-,

00:45:25.530 --> 00:45:31.400
they don't really wanna hear your solution
to this. They wanna talk about it and you're

00:45:31.400 --> 00:45:34.630
solution might have nothing to do with the
problem.

00:45:34.630 --> 00:45:38.350
&gt;&gt;Ben: No, but you're a sounding board--

00:45:38.350 --> 00:45:40.630
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Yeah.

00:45:40.630 --> 00:45:42.720
&gt;&gt;Ben: and it's ok.

00:45:42.720 --> 00:45:43.720
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:45:43.720 --> 00:45:51.230
&gt;&gt;Ben: And it's good and if you can calm them
down and, and just emotionally get them focused

00:45:51.230 --> 00:45:55.600
again. It's a huge value, right? You're greasing
the wheels again.

00:45:55.600 --> 00:46:03.510
&gt;&gt;Fitz: And a part of this extends beyond
your team, right? Ask your team how you can

00:46:03.510 --> 00:46:11.070
be more productive and then measure that,
ok? Outside of the team you need to build

00:46:11.070 --> 00:46:19.150
relationships across the company and y-, you're
gonna be that bridge to other teams and that

00:46:19.150 --> 00:46:20.150
sort of thing.

00:46:20.150 --> 00:46:22.200
&gt;&gt;Ben: This, this next pattern we've talked
about in other talks; lose the ego. And, and

00:46:22.200 --> 00:46:36.090
people, people misinterpret what we mean by
this. We don't mean be a dead fish, have no,

00:46:36.090 --> 00:46:48.090
have no confidence. It actually just means
don't be egotistical, is what we're really

00:46:48.090 --> 00:46:49.090
saying.

00:46:49.090 --> 00:46:50.090
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:46:50.090 --> 00:46:56.830
&gt;&gt;Ben: So, we have, we have particular i-,
examples of losing ego, right? Actually trusting

00:46:56.830 --> 00:47:00.900
your team. They're down in the trenches every
day doing stuff. It's ok. They know more than

00:47:00.900 --> 00:47:04.970
you. They probably should know more than you,
right? If they tell you something is or isn't

00:47:04.970 --> 00:47:08.030
possible, listen. Because they know, right?
And you're not down--

00:47:08.030 --> 00:47:13.380
&gt;&gt;Fitz: But when it comes to the details of
the particular--

00:47:13.380 --> 00:47:14.880
&gt;Ben: The details--

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:16.380
&gt;&gt;Fitz: area, right?

00:47:16.380 --> 00:47:21.830
&gt;&gt;Ben: Have some respect for their abilities,
for the accomplishments that they've done

00:47:21.830 --> 00:47:26.000
so far, for, for what they've learned, what
they know, what they're able to tell you from

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:28.920
being down in the trenches.

00:47:28.920 --> 00:47:39.990
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Then, and the next one is, is something,
Appreciate Inquiry. You should always actually

00:47:39.990 --> 00:47:46.970
accept when someone gives you feedback or
criticism. And try not to be territorial about

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:57.090
things. Try and think big picture. Now, I
think this is really important in the, in

00:47:57.090 --> 00:48:04.220
the high-tech world when you're writing software.
I learned the hard way that this isn't necessarily

00:48:04.220 --> 00:48:06.400
appreciated in other domains. I--

00:48:06.400 --> 00:48:07.400
[Ben laughs]

00:48:07.400 --> 00:48:16.250
I had a, a friend of mine and an electrician
helping me rewire the basement in my house

00:48:16.250 --> 00:48:20.580
and I was so excited about this cause I'm
learning about stuff electrical. And I asked

00:48:20.580 --> 00:48:24.610
this electrician about seven thousand questions.
And, and I'm thinking, "Wow, I'm learning

00:48:24.610 --> 00:48:29.960
all this cool stuff!" And he's thinking, "This
guy doesn't trust me at all." Right?

00:48:29.960 --> 00:48:30.960
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yeah.

00:48:30.960 --> 00:48:38.910
&gt;&gt;Fitz: But, in, in our, in, in high tech
again, when you're working on software development

00:48:38.910 --> 00:48:42.000
this is something that's really important
to, to listen if someone, if someone's questioning

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:47.640
something you're doing it's good to talk through
it because they might actually have a good

00:48:47.640 --> 00:48:49.210
idea for you.

00:48:49.210 --> 00:48:54.530
&gt;&gt;Ben: Well, usually it's curious interest,
right?

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:55.780
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:48:55.780 --> 00:49:03.830
&gt;&gt;Ben: That's, that's, maybe that's part of
hacker cultures that, when somebody asks you

00:49:03.830 --> 00:49:08.430
lots of questions it's usually cause they're
just interested, not because they're questioning--

00:49:08.430 --> 00:49:14.480
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right. But, but annoying the hell
out of somebody leads great into the next

00:49:14.480 --> 00:49:16.240
thing which is to apologize.

00:49:16.240 --> 00:49:21.880
&gt;&gt;Ben: Apologizing. There's, it's, it's so
crazy that we have to put this slide up, right?

00:49:21.880 --> 00:49:28.190
But so many people are just afraid to apologize.
I see this all the time where they messed

00:49:28.190 --> 00:49:33.930
up, they know they messed up, and the manager's
usually the last person to apologize, right?

00:49:33.930 --> 00:49:40.150
And it's ok, it's really, again, it's about
being, it's about having some humility.

00:49:40.150 --> 00:49:44.530
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, that's about being a human, right?
I mean, everybody certainly make mistakes

00:49:44.530 --> 00:49:51.380
and, and especially if someone gives you constructive
feedback, you go like, "Wow, I can't believe

00:49:51.380 --> 00:49:52.920
I did that. I apologize."

00:49:52.920 --> 00:50:03.630
&gt;&gt;Ben: I know it when, when, when my managers
in the past have apologized it just increases

00:50:03.630 --> 00:50:11.370
my respect for them, right, all the more.

00:50:11.370 --> 00:50:18.491
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Yeah, so, ba-, back, again to stress
the humility part, this doesn't mean you have

00:50:18.491 --> 00:50:19.690
be a doormat.

00:50:19.690 --> 00:50:20.780
[Ben laughs]

00:50:20.780 --> 00:50:24.410
This doesn't mean, it, it's not the same as,
as being unconfident, right? If, you can still

00:50:24.410 --> 00:50:30.720
have self confidence and have opinions and
this is the fine line. This is a lo-, this

00:50:30.720 --> 00:50:37.590
is a really hard thing I think for some people.
Some people have no problem with it, you know?

00:50:37.590 --> 00:50:38.590
[Ben laughs]

00:50:38.590 --> 00:50:39.590
But--

00:50:39.590 --> 00:50:45.110
&gt;&gt;Ben: Part of getting some respect from,
from peers also, like we've said before, is

00:50:45.110 --> 00:50:51.580
getting your hands dirty. Like, effectively,
it's ok to go down in the trenches sometimes,

00:50:51.580 --> 00:50:56.890
or maybe you're curious, or maybe you wanna
learn, or maybe you wanna help. And I think

00:50:56.890 --> 00:51:04.130
it's good to occasionally do that if you have,
if you have the time and the bandwidth, right?

00:51:04.130 --> 00:51:13.070
Cuz it'll help you understand the problems
that your team are dealing with more.

00:51:13.070 --> 00:51:17.290
&gt;&gt;Fitz: You get a lot of respect and it, it
shows that you're not just here to contribute

00:51:17.290 --> 00:51:18.290
advice.

00:51:18.290 --> 00:51:19.290
&gt;&gt;Ben: The next thing--

00:51:19.290 --> 00:51:33.570
&gt;&gt;Fitz: And that's, that's again, and that's
if you have time. If you're like swamped out

00:51:33.570 --> 00:51:38.300
of your mind and doing way more than you can
already do.

00:51:38.300 --> 00:51:47.670
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right. But the next thing is actually
hard for, for new managers. I know it took

00:51:47.670 --> 00:51:53.540
me a long time to figure this out is that
people don't delegate, right? The classic

00:51:53.540 --> 00:52:00.220
new manager is like, "Ok, I'm in charge of
like, instead of this charge of one thing,

00:52:00.220 --> 00:52:09.920
I'm in charge of ten things now. So, I'm gonna
try and do it all myself and ask people to

00:52:09.920 --> 00:52:15.650
help me." And like, no, you still can only
do one thing, which is to make sure the other

00:52:15.650 --> 00:52:18.820
ten people are doing the ten things, right,
that you delegated, right?

00:52:18.820 --> 00:52:20.141
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, and you, you see something,
you'll see a task that one of your junior

00:52:20.141 --> 00:52:21.720
guys is gonna take three weeks to do when
you can do it in three days and the temptation

00:52:21.720 --> 00:52:25.220
is overwhelming to, to do that thing for them.
And that's when you need to stop, right? Deep

00:52:25.220 --> 00:52:28.540
breath, back up a little bit. But that leads
into the next thing of, of delegating. If

00:52:28.540 --> 00:52:29.540
you get a team that's doing enough stuff--

00:52:29.540 --> 00:52:30.540
&gt;&gt;Ben: Self powered.

00:52:30.540 --> 00:52:31.540
&gt;&gt;Fitz: that's self empowered, right. And
there, you hire people a little smarter than

00:52:31.540 --> 00:52:32.540
you, right? Just look to replace yourself,
ok?

00:52:32.540 --> 00:52:33.540
&gt;&gt;Ben: Sounds crazy but that's what sys admins
do, right? Try to replace themselves with

00:52:33.540 --> 00:52:34.540
shell scripts so they can play, play games
at work.

00:52:34.540 --> 00:52:38.640
&gt;&gt;Fitz: If you can replace yourself in a shell
script, that's great, too. You can find something

00:52:38.640 --> 00:52:40.000
else to do, I'm sure.

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:41.000
[Ben laughs]

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:43.100
Anyone writes a management shell script, please
email it to me. That would be great.

00:52:43.100 --> 00:52:44.100
[audience laughter]

00:52:44.100 --> 00:52:51.560
&gt;&gt;Ben: But this is, but this is, I think this
is, this is a measurement of success in management,

00:52:51.560 --> 00:53:00.050
right? If you can take a team that is not
performing well at all; lots of fighting,

00:53:00.050 --> 00:53:05.900
lots of confusion and you can sort of push
people in different ways.

00:53:05.900 --> 00:53:09.510
So, they're still self powered, but they've
become this well-oiled machine to the point

00:53:09.510 --> 00:53:16.220
where you can almost just step back and you
barely need to touch that machine anymore.

00:53:16.220 --> 00:53:19.150
You're done, right? That is what they're paying
you to do. That's what it means to be a leader.

00:53:19.150 --> 00:53:22.630
And then you can move on to another team,
right?

00:53:22.630 --> 00:53:26.630
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right, and if you have, so you have
these capable peo-, if, bas-, what I think,

00:53:26.630 --> 00:53:29.540
focus on what people can do and try and always
give them a little more responsibility than

00:53:29.540 --> 00:53:30.540
what they can actually d-, take, take on.
Without killing them, right? You don't wanna

00:53:30.540 --> 00:53:32.340
like, drive these people into the ground but
you just want to give them the opportunity

00:53:32.340 --> 00:53:33.340
to grow into that.

00:53:33.340 --> 00:53:37.490
If they feel a little bit overwhelmed, or,
or push back and realize they can't do that,

00:53:37.490 --> 00:53:44.680
then that's ok. You should always give them
the chance because if you cave somebody, they're

00:53:44.680 --> 00:53:50.810
never gonna be able to show you what they
can do. And, and you'll often be surprised.

00:53:50.810 --> 00:53:53.430
&gt;&gt;Ben: Your successor usually comes from within
the team.

00:53:53.430 --> 00:53:54.570
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:53:54.570 --> 00:53:57.440
&gt;&gt;Ben: It's a great thing.

00:53:57.440 --> 00:54:04.910
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, I wanna talk about, briefly about
making waves, ok? Know when to make waves.

00:54:04.910 --> 00:54:05.910
[Ben laughs]

00:54:05.910 --> 00:54:06.910
Right? Th-, that's, I was told that piece
of advice and for, because I was basic-, well,

00:54:06.910 --> 00:54:07.910
I don't wanna talk--

00:54:07.910 --> 00:54:08.910
&gt;&gt;Ben: Google Wave?

00:54:08.910 --> 00:54:09.910
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Not these kinda waves, I'm sorry.
It's, it's these kind of waves. I had someone

00:54:09.910 --> 00:54:10.910
who I, who I, who reported to me who was making
my life complete hell and I was hoping it

00:54:10.910 --> 00:54:11.910
would go away. This ties into the sort of
hoping things will get better, right? There

00:54:11.910 --> 00:54:12.910
are times when you're leading a team that
every ounce of your soul is gonna tell you,

00:54:12.910 --> 00:54:13.910
"Just be that calm center of the world."

00:54:13.910 --> 00:54:14.910
&gt;&gt;Ben: Don't rock the boat.

00:54:14.910 --> 00:54:15.910
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Don't rock the boat. There's something
crazy going on, you just mellow out and it'll

00:54:15.910 --> 00:54:16.910
be ok. And that's the time when you should
be just like cannonball and jump right in

00:54:16.910 --> 00:54:18.040
and, and make some waves in that team. You
should attack it head on, again in a constructive

00:54:18.040 --> 00:54:19.040
manner, but it's one of those things that's
not gonna wind up--

00:54:19.040 --> 00:54:20.040
&gt;&gt;Ben: Or sometimes, sometimes it's beyond
your team. Sometimes it's things happening

00:54:20.040 --> 00:54:24.160
in teams adjacent to you or within the company
and if you ignore it, you're in trouble, right?

00:54:24.160 --> 00:54:30.650
So, yeah, it's hard to break that inertia,
that the, the instinct to just curl up and

00:54:30.650 --> 00:54:32.130
just focus and stay safe.

00:54:32.130 --> 00:54:35.360
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right. And that, and another thing--

00:54:35.360 --> 00:54:36.360
&gt;&gt;Ben: It's easier.

00:54:36.360 --> 00:54:37.360
&gt;&gt;Fitz: We, we, we've sort of touched on this
already but shield your team from distractions

00:54:37.360 --> 00:54:44.830
from outside of your, outside, right? Usually,
there's a lot of crazy things going on in

00:54:44.830 --> 00:54:45.830
the bureaucracy of the company or in the upper
echelons, and you should, or politics, bureaucracy,

00:54:45.830 --> 00:54:46.830
that sort of thing. And basically, allow your
team, give them the luxury of focusing on

00:54:46.830 --> 00:54:47.830
what they wanna get done.

00:54:47.830 --> 00:54:48.830
&gt;&gt;Ben: This next idea is actually, I think
it's more about language, its, it's a very

00:54:48.830 --> 00:54:50.690
specific language tip. The, the worst thing
I've seen happen is maybe your service falls

00:54:50.690 --> 00:54:52.100
over and it's one person's fault on the team;
they messed up, right? Took down your whole

00:54:52.100 --> 00:54:53.100
service.

00:54:53.100 --> 00:54:54.100
The, the wrong thing to do is to say, "Our
service was down because of Joe." Right? And

00:54:54.100 --> 00:54:56.430
you embarrass that person in front of the
whole team, right? That is not the way to

00:54:56.430 --> 00:54:59.830
do it. What you, what we talk about is when
somebody messes up, they know, right? And

00:54:59.830 --> 00:55:00.850
you have, and--

00:55:00.850 --> 00:55:01.850
&gt;&gt;Fitz: The team knows.

00:55:01.850 --> 00:55:03.770
&gt;&gt;Ben: The team knows and you know and the
person knows, right? And you don't need to

00:55:03.770 --> 00:55:05.420
publically humiliate or shame somebody. That's,
that's a stick, right? That's Industrial Revolution

00:55:05.420 --> 00:55:07.560
stick mentality. What you do is you; you talk
about it in private, in a one-on-one. And

00:55:07.560 --> 00:55:12.210
say what happened and blah, blah, blah, you
know, what can we do to stop it in the future?

00:55:12.210 --> 00:55:17.840
So, I mean, when talking openly to your team
or talking to the company about your team,

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:21.852
you talk about we succeed and fail as a, particularly,
you do public praise of an individual, but

00:55:21.852 --> 00:55:22.852
you privately criticize someone, right? So,
"Hey, our team succeeded. Isn't that great?

00:55:22.852 --> 00:55:23.852
And super thanks to this person for helping
out in this way, right?" Or, "Oh, our service

00:55:23.852 --> 00:55:24.852
went down and we failed as a team, we'll get
better at that."

00:55:24.852 --> 00:55:25.852
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right.

00:55:25.852 --> 00:55:26.852
&gt;&gt;Ben: And then you take that one person aside
in private and talk about it, right? So, it's,

00:55:26.852 --> 00:55:27.852
it's just, it's just the way you handle it.
There, there's a tactfulness that's important.

00:55:27.852 --> 00:55:28.852
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right. And another thing you should
look to do as a manager is to, is to build

00:55:28.852 --> 00:55:29.852
consensus, right? You need to be that cata-,
catalyst that people can help make things

00:55:29.852 --> 00:55:30.852
happen, right? You, if know, if, you need
to know when to get your team unstuck, ok,

00:55:30.852 --> 00:55:31.852
or when to take a risk, but, but also, you
should be there to take responsibility for

00:55:31.852 --> 00:55:34.500
the failures if you're pushing things along.

00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:36.660
&gt;&gt;Ben: Being a teacher, or a mentor. This
helps if you're older, I guess, or have some

00:55:36.660 --> 00:55:37.760
more experience. But, especially when you've
got new people on the team, right? Either

00:55:37.760 --> 00:55:39.130
assign them a mentor, or try to mentor them
yourselves. Letting them, we've talked about

00:55:39.130 --> 00:55:41.240
this a few times already, but letting them
make mistakes and not jumping in and doing

00:55:41.240 --> 00:55:42.240
it for them. Letting them goof up and learn
and--

00:55:42.240 --> 00:55:43.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: It's the whole failure is an option
thing, right? Failure is ok as long as you're

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:44.240
not failing at the same thing over and over
and over again.

00:55:44.240 --> 00:55:45.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: You should tell your antidote.

00:55:45.240 --> 00:55:46.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: There's a, well, there's a, there's
a story about the, the senior executive that

00:55:46.240 --> 00:55:47.240
made a big business mistake and lost his company
ten million dollars and he comes in the next

00:55:47.240 --> 00:55:48.240
morning. He's all depressed cause he's gonna
lose his job and the secretary calls him,

00:55:48.240 --> 00:55:49.240
"The CEO wants to see you in his office."
So, he goes into the office, he's like, "I

00:55:49.240 --> 00:55:50.240
suppose you'd like my resignation and here
