00:55:50.240 --> 00:55:51.240
want your resignation? I just spent ten million
dollars training you." Right?

00:55:51.240 --> 00:55:52.240
[audience laughs]

00:55:52.240 --> 00:55:53.240
So, that, that's a bit of a severe example
of a failure or mistake, but--

00:55:53.240 --> 00:55:54.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: But letting people iterate and fail
is important.

00:55:54.240 --> 00:55:55.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: But I guarantee he'll never make that
mistake again.

00:55:55.240 --> 00:55:56.240
[Ben laughs]

00:55:56.240 --> 00:55:57.240
Ok? And so, just, just to, to move on here,
set, this is getting a little bit long here

00:55:57.240 --> 00:55:58.240
but--

00:55:58.240 --> 00:55:59.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: It's a good story.

00:55:59.240 --> 00:56:00.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Set clear goals. Your, your team needs
to agree on the plans and you really, I think

00:56:00.240 --> 00:56:01.240
a mission statement is one of those corporate
double-speak things that people freak out

00:56:01.240 --> 00:56:02.240
about. It's really important. If you sit down
and try to come up with like a quick sentence

00:56:02.240 --> 00:56:03.240
to convey what you're doing, it's gonna really
cause you to come up with a moment of clarity

00:56:03.240 --> 00:56:04.240
in your team, and you'll probably find out
you don't all agree on where you're going.

00:56:04.240 --> 00:56:05.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: It's, it's surprising, actually. I
mean, if you took a survey of your teams and

00:56:05.240 --> 00:56:06.240
said, "What is the mission of this thing we're
working on?" You're gonna get different answers

00:56:06.240 --> 00:56:07.240
unless you've already sat down and, and written
a mission statement together and it, it sounds,

00:56:07.240 --> 00:56:08.240
it sounds hokey?

00:56:08.240 --> 00:56:09.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Yeah.

00:56:09.240 --> 00:56:10.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: But it makes a huge difference in getting
focused, right? And we're not talking about

00:56:10.240 --> 00:56:11.240
hiring a business consultant, spending weeks
to, to tal-, just have, sit down over lunch,

00:56:11.240 --> 00:56:12.240
or sit down for a couple hours and have this
conversation. Because it's amazing when things,

00:56:12.240 --> 00:56:13.240
your, you're bombarded with distractions all
the time, right?

00:56:13.240 --> 00:56:14.240
Other teams telling you we want this feature
or that thing or we're gonna do this, and

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:15.240
if you have a written mission statement, it's
very easy to know what is in your scope and

00:56:15.240 --> 00:56:16.240
what isn't, right?

00:56:16.240 --> 00:56:17.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: The Google Web Toolkit--

00:56:17.240 --> 00:56:18.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: It's a huge time saver.

00:56:18.240 --> 00:56:19.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: You know, I worked with the Google
Web Toolkit team four years ago now to wor-,

00:56:19.240 --> 00:56:20.240
with their mission statement and I was talking
to Bruce Johnson who, if you've ever met him

00:56:20.240 --> 00:56:21.240
he's a fantastic guy, I told him, I said,
"I really wanna tell ya-" he said, he told

00:56:21.240 --> 00:56:22.240
me how great that was for their team. He's
like, "I never realized how unfocused we were

00:56:22.240 --> 00:56:23.240
until we came up with that." And I said, "I'm
really appreciative of you being so supportive

00:56:23.240 --> 00:56:24.240
of me at the time to do this because I know
some of your team members didn't want to do

00:56:24.240 --> 00:56:25.240
it." He said, "Oh, I really thought it was
a waste of time." He said, --

00:56:25.240 --> 00:56:26.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: --At the moment, right?

00:56:26.240 --> 00:56:27.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: "But at the moment I wanted to give
you a try." And it turned out to be one of

00:56:27.240 --> 00:56:28.240
the greatest things that--

00:56:28.240 --> 00:56:29.240
[Ben laughs]

00:56:29.240 --> 00:56:30.240
that sort of helped them to focus and say,
learn when to say no and when to say yes and

00:56:30.240 --> 00:56:31.240
that sort of thing.

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:32.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: And this, I, this, this is the last
pattern, I think? Yes, yes--

00:56:32.240 --> 00:56:33.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: I hope so.

00:56:33.240 --> 00:56:34.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Finally.

00:56:34.240 --> 00:56:35.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Are we done yet?

00:56:35.240 --> 00:56:36.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: When we've mentioned this before, right,
about your job is not just to, technical health.

00:56:36.240 --> 00:56:37.240
It's the social health as well. Right? Have
a happiness meter. Ask yourself; meet with

00:56:37.240 --> 00:56:38.240
your reports once a month. Before you go into
your meetings or one-on-ones with them, say,

00:56:38.240 --> 00:56:39.240
"Is this person happy?" And then ask them.
Say," Are you happy?" I mean, it's, it's a

00:56:39.240 --> 00:56:40.240
crazy question and a lot of people are taken
back and they'll say, "Yes, I am." or "No,

00:56:40.240 --> 00:56:41.240
I'm not and, and here's why. I've been afraid
to tell you." Right? I mean, it's, it really

00:56:41.240 --> 00:56:42.240
matters.

00:56:42.240 --> 00:56:43.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: One of the, the scariest questions
I've ever been asked by a person in management

00:56:43.240 --> 00:56:44.240
to me is, "What can I do for you? What do
you need from me?" And the first time I was

00:56:44.240 --> 00:56:45.240
asked this, I was just like, "What kind of
question is this?"

00:56:45.240 --> 00:56:46.240
[Ben laughs]

00:56:46.240 --> 00:56:47.240
What are you supposed to say? But I thought
about it a lot and the next time they said,

00:56:47.240 --> 00:56:48.240
"What do you need me?" I was, man, I was ready.

00:56:48.240 --> 00:56:49.240
[Fitz laughs]

00:56:49.240 --> 00:56:50.240
[audience laughs]

00:56:50.240 --> 00:56:51.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: But, but sometimes I've seen managers,
who are very technical, who take this to heart,

00:56:51.240 --> 00:56:52.240
but the way they deal with it is a very super
technical solution. They'll make a spreadsheet

00:56:52.240 --> 00:56:53.240
and they'll track, you know, here's all the
people on the team and here's all the tasks,

00:56:53.240 --> 00:56:54.240
and these tasks are fun, and these tasks are
horrible, and I'm gonna assign the tasks this

00:56:54.240 --> 00:56:55.240
way and then the next week I'm gonna rotate,
I'm gonna ro-, so everybody gets a chance

00:56:55.240 --> 00:56:56.240
to, to be miserable and happy and everything's
fair. And that's fine. If it, if it works,

00:56:56.240 --> 00:56:57.240
that's great, right? But then, at least, he's
still monitoring the happiness level, right?

00:56:57.240 --> 00:56:58.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, what Ben's saying is spread the
misery around.

00:56:58.240 --> 00:56:59.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Spread the--

00:56:59.240 --> 00:57:00.240
[Ben laughs]

00:57:00.240 --> 00:57:01.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right?

00:57:01.240 --> 00:57:02.240
[audience laughs]

00:57:02.240 --> 00:57:03.240
But, but, by doing this you actually give
everybody a chance to be seen by others outside

00:57:03.240 --> 00:57:04.240
of the team and a lot of times--

00:57:04.240 --> 00:57:05.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: --to grow.

00:57:05.240 --> 00:57:06.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: That's also important, right?

00:57:06.240 --> 00:57:07.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Absolutely.

00:57:07.240 --> 00:57:08.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: So, ok, enough with the patterns.

00:57:08.240 --> 00:57:09.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Let's, let's do our wrap up which is
longer than the middle, no, I'm kidding.

00:57:09.240 --> 00:57:10.240
[Ben laughs]

00:57:10.240 --> 00:57:11.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: No. So, I think I should tell you
a, a story that, that, this is my mother-in-law's

00:57:11.240 --> 00:57:12.240
philosophy, ok? My, my wife is the last of
six children and my mother-in-laws philosophy

00:57:12.240 --> 00:57:13.240
is about kids is that, and I think it applies
to engineers as well, ok? So, engineers are

00:57:13.240 --> 00:57:14.240
like plants. Everyone needs something different.
Some engineers need more water. Some engineers

00:57:14.240 --> 00:57:15.240
need more sunlight and some engineers need
to be buried in bullshit, ok?

00:57:15.240 --> 00:57:16.240
[laughter]

00:57:16.240 --> 00:57:17.240
Your job as their caretaker or leader is to
know who needs what, ok? Applying the same

00:57:17.240 --> 00:57:18.240
amount of water, sunlight, and bullshit to
everybody means that some people are gonna

00:57:18.240 --> 00:57:19.240
get way too much of something they don't need
and some people are gonna get way too little

00:57:19.240 --> 00:57:20.240
of something they don't need.

00:57:20.240 --> 00:57:21.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Now, now let's do the spreadsheet version!

00:57:21.240 --> 00:57:22.240
[Ben laughs]

00:57:22.240 --> 00:57:23.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Spreadsheet version.

00:57:23.240 --> 00:57:24.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: This is, this comes out of various
management classes that we've seen and you

00:57:24.240 --> 00:57:25.240
might have seen as well, right? Putting people
