00:57:31.240 --> 00:57:32.240
some direction, right? Not all direction is
micromanagement, right?

00:57:32.240 --> 00:57:33.240
Some people actually need micromanagement,
as long as it's just for a little bit, right?

00:57:33.240 --> 00:57:34.240
Not, not if it's all the time, if they need
it all the time, something's wrong, but bits

00:57:34.240 --> 00:57:35.240
of direction here and there are great. Get
them, get them self-supporting, right?

00:57:35.240 --> 00:57:36.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: And you might have some people that
aren't challenged enough, or aren't--

00:57:36.240 --> 00:57:37.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right.

00:57:37.240 --> 00:57:38.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: regularly focused on what they're
doing, or--

00:57:38.240 --> 00:57:39.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Or they hate what they're doing.

00:57:39.240 --> 00:57:40.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right. And so, they're gonna need
some inspiration, right? They're gonna need

00:57:40.240 --> 00:57:41.240
some sort of, you're gonna have to figure
out some way to motivate them and we'll talk

00:57:41.240 --> 00:57:42.240
a little about--

00:57:42.240 --> 00:57:43.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Let's talk about, let's talk about
motivation--

00:57:43.240 --> 00:57:44.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: About motivation.

00:57:44.240 --> 00:57:45.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: This is, this is the stuff from Dan
Pink's talk, right?

00:57:45.240 --> 00:57:46.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: This is a great picture; by the way,
it's a carrot on a stick.

00:57:46.240 --> 00:57:47.240
[Ben laughs]

00:57:47.240 --> 00:57:48.240
So there's the carrot and there's the work
you just beat with the stick.

00:57:48.240 --> 00:57:49.240
[laughter]

00:57:49.240 --> 00:57:50.240
Ok?

00:57:50.240 --> 00:57:51.240
[Ben coughs]

00:57:51.240 --> 00:57:52.240
So that doesn't work in this place, right?

00:57:52.240 --> 00:57:53.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: So, how many people have heard "Intrinsic
vs. Extrinsic Motivations?" It's a trendy

00:57:53.240 --> 00:57:54.240
topic now, right? The idea is that these carrot
and stick work faster, that's, that's extrinsic

00:57:54.240 --> 00:57:55.240
motivation, right? It's, its motivation coming
artificially from the outside and on now the

00:57:55.240 --> 00:57:56.240
cool thing in management, which I believe
in, which science confirms, is that--

00:57:56.240 --> 00:57:57.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: --Science!

00:57:57.240 --> 00:57:58.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: --Science!

00:57:58.240 --> 00:57:59.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: --It works!

00:57:59.240 --> 00:58:00.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right. Is intrinsic motivations, in
other words, getting, getting people motivated

00:58:00.240 --> 00:58:01.240
internally, right? And it's not about waving
money in front of them, right? It, it's getting

00:58:01.240 --> 00:58:02.240
them to actually care about what they're working
on and there's, there's three big parts to

00:58:02.240 --> 00:58:03.240
this that you can name--

00:58:03.240 --> 00:58:04.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, but you can never get anyone
to, to, to work as, as hard, or care as they

00:58:04.240 --> 00:58:05.240
do extrinsic mot-, intrinsic--

00:58:05.240 --> 00:58:06.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Right.

00:58:06.240 --> 00:58:07.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: extrinsic motivations, right? And
this is the whole Dan Pink thing, right?

00:58:07.240 --> 00:58:08.240
&gt;Ben: So what are the three big intrinsic
motivations? The first one is autonomy, right?

00:58:08.240 --> 00:58:09.240
In other words, trusting people to work the
way that they work best, right? If that means

00:58:09.240 --> 00:58:10.240
working from home once in awhile, if that
means having some flexibility in, in who they're

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:11.240
working with, or how they're doing their work,
that's fine. There's a, there's a, let them

00:58:11.240 --> 00:58:12.240
get their work; they know how to work best,
right? You can't shoehorn--

00:58:12.240 --> 00:58:13.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, the 20 percent time is an example
of that, right? The, we, we, they get 20 percent

00:58:13.240 --> 00:58:14.240
time to engineers at Google. A lot of the
time, there's, the, they always talk about

00:58:14.240 --> 00:58:15.240
what products came out of 20 percent time.
But, a lot of time it's just permission to

00:58:15.240 --> 00:58:16.240
go chase something down that's bugging you,
right? If you have an idea in your head and

00:58:16.240 --> 00:58:17.240
you sit around and think, "This is this great
idea, it's a great idea. It's just gonna rot

00:58:17.240 --> 00:58:18.240
there."

00:58:18.240 --> 00:58:19.240
And, and you go on thinking, "I have this
great idea." And if you took four or five

00:58:19.240 --> 00:58:20.240
hours, you might actually get to realize,
"Well, it wasn't such a great idea but it

00:58:20.240 --> 00:58:21.240
was interesting and I learned this, this and
this. Now I can go back to everything else

00:58:21.240 --> 00:58:22.240
and focus more." And just, you have that sort
of freedom to pursue.

00:58:22.240 --> 00:58:23.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: The, the next motivation is, is what
we call mastery. Giving people the opportunity

00:58:23.240 --> 00:58:24.240
to learn and grow, right? I mean, it's great
to be an expert in something and maybe some

00:58:24.240 --> 00:58:25.240
people view it as job security, but let me
tell you, you get really bored after awhile,

00:58:25.240 --> 00:58:26.240
right?

00:58:26.240 --> 00:58:27.240
And if you're not, and if your manager isn't
giving you a chance to learn new things and

00:58:27.240 --> 00:58:28.240
get better at something, then, then you're
gonna be frustrated, right? And if it's like,

00:58:28.240 --> 00:58:29.240
you're really interested, if there's a chance
to learn something new, you're gonna get,

00:58:29.240 --> 00:58:30.240
you're gonna get excited.

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:31.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Well, how many people in this room
participate in the hiring process where they

00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:32.240
work? Ok. Whoa. A lot, that's great. I, there's
a, there's a analogy that I like to use is

00:58:32.240 --> 00:58:33.240
that we're all out there looking for the sharpest
knife in the drawer, right?

00:58:33.240 --> 00:58:34.240
[Ben laughs]

00:58:34.240 --> 00:58:35.240
We all wanna hire the sharpest knife, ok?
There's two things you can do once you get

00:58:35.240 --> 00:58:36.240
that knife in your hand, ok? You can go outside
and you can grind it in the sidewalk until

00:58:36.240 --> 00:58:37.240
it's dull.

00:58:37.240 --> 00:58:38.240
[Ben laughs]

00:58:38.240 --> 00:58:39.240
And then you say, "I have a dull knife." And
you throw it away and you go looking for another

00:58:39.240 --> 00:58:40.240
knife, and, "I have a sharp knife." And then
you grind it down, right? And there's this,

00:58:40.240 --> 00:58:41.240
this sort of burn, this is the process of
burning people out and not giving them a chance

00:58:41.240 --> 00:58:42.240
to learn and grow. You wanna focus on getting
that sharp knife, but keeping it sharp.

00:58:42.240 --> 00:58:43.240
Give people opportunities to learn new technology;
to learn new things. Sometimes, it doesn't

00:58:43.240 --> 00:58:44.240
even have to be directly related to what you're
doing. We're, we're doing a thing in our Chicago

00:58:44.240 --> 00:58:45.240
office right now, we're having robot contests
now, right? We're building Mindstorm robots

00:58:45.240 --> 00:58:46.240
and--

00:58:46.240 --> 00:58:47.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Yup.

00:58:47.240 --> 00:58:48.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: pitting them against each other in
various ways. Arguably, I don't think we're

00:58:48.240 --> 00:58:49.240
gonna be shipping any robots any time soon
for, for our projects in Chicago--

00:58:49.240 --> 00:58:50.240
[Ben laughs]

00:58:50.240 --> 00:58:51.240
but, this, it gives people a chance to get
to know each other, they're learning new stuff--

00:58:51.240 --> 00:58:52.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: Work together.

00:58:52.240 --> 00:58:53.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: they're working together, etc. And
it's just one example of many, right.

00:58:53.240 --> 00:58:54.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: So, the last, last intrinsic motivation
is just giving people a sense of purpose,

00:58:54.240 --> 00:58:55.240
right? We, we've talked in other, in other
talks about letting people drive the bus,

00:58:55.240 --> 00:58:56.240
right, and not just one driver. Let them work
on something they care about, give them a

00:58:56.240 --> 00:58:57.240
sense of ownership or stake, right? And it
isn't just some thing that's being handed

00:58:57.240 --> 00:58:58.240
down from the highest levels of management
and they're just a cog in, in the machine.

00:58:58.240 --> 00:58:59.240
Let them actually have an opinion, have a
voice, direct where it's going, right? Take

00:58:59.240 --> 00:59:00.240
turns giving the direction.

00:59:00.240 --> 00:59:01.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Right, cuz if you follow all of this
stuff and you hired really smart people who

00:59:01.240 --> 00:59:02.240
are really motivated, they're gonna wanna
work on something really big like that. I

00:59:02.240 --> 00:59:03.240
interviewed a guy once and I said, "If you
could do anything in the world, what would

00:59:03.240 --> 00:59:04.240
you wanna do?" And he sat there and he looked
up and he thought for a second and he said,

00:59:04.240 --> 00:59:05.240
"I just wanna add value." And I was horrified
by that--

00:59:05.240 --> 00:59:06.240
&gt;&gt;Ben: [laughs] I wanna add value.

00:59:06.240 --> 00:59:07.240
&gt;&gt;Fitz: Really, that's all you can come up
with? I give you any opportunity to do anything

00:59:07.240 --> 00:59:08.240
and you want to add value, add value to what?
I mean, are you an adding machine?

00:59:08.240 --> 00:59:09.240
[audience and Ben laughter]

